data.content:
Hash Table
The hash table is a directory implementation method that uses a hash function on filenames to quickly locate corresponding directory entries in a list.

Memory
Memory is used to cache active directory information to reduce repeated disk access and improve system performance.<SEP>Memory is the storage location where the VFS exists and dynamically manages file system objects during system operation.

Disk I/O Operation
Disk I/O operation refers to reading from or writing to disk storage, which is a costly and time-consuming process.

Linear List
The linear list is a basic directory implementation method that uses a sequential arrangement of filename and data block pointer pairs for storing directory entries.

Directory Entry
A directory entry is a data structure that holds the name and physical location of a file in storage.<SEP>Directory entry is a data structure in a directory that contains a file name and a pointer to the corresponding index node.<SEP>The Directory Entry is a data structure that contains metadata about a file, including its name and storage location.<SEP>Directory Entry is a component of a file directory that contains a file name and a reference to its index node.<SEP>A directory entry is a data structure in a directory that stores information about a file or subdirectory, such as name and location.

Data Block Pointer
Data block pointer contains information required to locate the physical disk blocks where file data is stored.

File System
The file system is a logical structure for organizing and managing data on storage devices, including directory mechanisms.<SEP>The File System is a component of the operating system that manages file creation, storage, access, and maintenance, enabling users to interact with files without understanding underlying storage details.<SEP>A file system is a method used by an operating system to organize and manage files and directories on a storage device.<SEP>A file system provides efficient and convenient access to disk storage, enabling data storage, location, and retrieval through structured organization and management.<SEP>The file system is a logical structure that manages how data is stored and retrieved, including access control and file protection mechanisms.<SEP>A file system is an organized method for storing and retrieving files on storage devices.<SEP>The file system is a component of an operating system responsible for managing files and directories, including storage, retrieval, and access control.

File Name
File name is a unique identifier used to locate files in a directory structure.<SEP>A file name is a unique identifier assigned to a file, used for easy retrieval and classification.<SEP>The File Name is a string used to identify a file in a directory, used during initial file lookup but not required after opening.<SEP>File Name is a unique identifier for a file used in directory lookup and is stored directly in directory entries.

File Deletion
File deletion involves searching for a file by name, releasing its allocated space, and managing the freed directory entry.<SEP>File deletion refers to the process of removing a file, which only occurs when the link count reaches zero, ensuring no dangling references remain.

File Directory
File directory is a data structure used by the operating system to manage and locate files via their names.<SEP>File Directory is a collection of file control blocks, often stored on disk, and functions as a logical file that contains directory entries.<SEP>A file directory is a data structure managed by the file system that organizes and tracks files, storing information such as file attributes, location, and access control.

File Creation
File creation requires checking for duplicate names, finding an available space, and adding a new directory entry.

Linear Search
Linear search is the method used in linear list directory implementation to locate a file by sequentially checking each entry.

Hash Collision
Hash collision occurs when two different filenames produce the same hash value, requiring conflict resolution mechanisms.

In-Memory Operation
In-memory operation refers to performing file directory access and manipulation within RAM instead of on disk, improving performance.

Disk Access
Disk access refers to the process of reading from or writing to a physical disk, which involves higher latency compared to memory access.

Hash Lookup
Hash lookup is the method used in hash table directory implementation to quickly find a file using a hash function.

Recorded File
Recorded file is a file composed of one or more records, also known as a structured file, where each record contains one or more data items.

File Physical Structure
File physical structure, also known as storage structure, describes how a file is organized on external storage and is invisible to users.<SEP>File Physical Structure refers to the organization and distribution of file data on physical storage devices, including allocation methods and storage space management.

Fixed-Length Record
Fixed-length record is a record where all records in a file have the same length, with data items located at the same position and size.

Stream File
Stream file is a simple file organization form composed of a sequence of characters, also known as an unstructured file, with length measured in bytes.

Indexed File
Indexed file uses an index table to improve record retrieval speed, especially for variable-length records, by storing pointers and lengths.

Variable-Length Record
Variable-length record is a record where the length of each record may differ, due to varying numbers of data items or variable data item sizes.

File Logical Structure
File logical structure refers to the organization of a file from the user's perspective, describing how data is logically arranged within the file regardless of storage medium characteristics.

Sequential File
Sequential file is a file where records are arranged in sequence, either based on insertion order (string structure) or sorted by key (ordered structure).

Indexed Sequential File
Indexed sequential file combines sequential and indexed file structures, using a primary index to locate groups of records before performing sequential search within the group.

Random Access
Random access allows direct access to any record in a file, typically supported by indexed and hash-based file structures.

Direct File
Direct file, also known as hash file, stores records based on a key value or its hash function result, allowing fast access but potentially causing collisions.

Data Processing
Data processing involves the manipulation and management of data in files, often requiring efficient file structures for performance.

Sequential Access
Sequential access refers to the process of reading or writing records in the order they are stored, common in sequential and stream files.

Index Table
Index table is a data structure that contains index entries for each record or group of records, supporting faster retrieval in indexed and indexed sequential files.<SEP>An index table is a data structure that stores block numbers, used in secondary or multi-level indexing systems.

Record Retrieval
Record retrieval refers to the process of locating and accessing a specific record within a file, which varies based on file type and structure.

Hash Function
Hash function transforms a key value into a physical address for direct record access in a hash file.

Storage Overhead
Storage overhead refers to the extra space required to maintain additional data structures like index tables, which increases storage requirements.

Collision
Collision occurs in hash files when different key values produce the same hash output, leading to potential record access issues.

Batch Operation
Batch operation refers to the processing of multiple records at once, where sequential files show the highest efficiency.

Fast Retrieval
Fixed-length records allow faster retrieval due to consistent data item positioning and able to support binary search.

Sequential Search
Variable-length records require sequential search for retrieval since record lengths vary and pointers must be traversed.

File System Mounting
File system mounting is the process of attaching a file system to a directory in the file hierarchy so it can be accessed by the operating system.

Mount Point
A mount point is a directory in the file system hierarchy where an additional file system is attached for access.

Volume
A volume is a logical storage unit with a directory tree structure and a pointer to a mounted file system.<SEP>A volume is a storage area that contains a file system and can be a partition, an entire disk, or a RAID set.

Directory Structure
A directory structure refers to the hierarchical organization of files and folders within a file system.<SEP>The directory structure organizes files and subdirectories hierarchically for efficient navigation and access.

Logical Device
A logical device refers to a partition on a physical disk that is treated as a separate device for file system management.

Drive Letter
A drive letter is a single character used by Windows to identify a volume or physical/logical drive.

Root File System
The root file system is the primary file system mounted at system startup and contains the kernel image.

Windows System
The Windows system manages file systems using a two-level directory structure with drive letters representing devices and volumes.

Unix System
The Unix system uses a hierarchical file system architecture where all file systems are mounted under the root.

File System Pointer
A file system pointer is a reference within a volume that directs the operating system to the actual mounted file system.

System Startup
System startup is the initial phase of the operating system boot process where the root file system is mounted.

User Mounting
User mounting refers to the manual attachment of a file system to a mount point by a user.

System Initialization
System initialization is the phase during which the operating system sets up system resources, including mounting file systems.

Path Format
The path format specifies the structure used to access a file, typically in the form of drive-letter:\path\to\file in Windows systems.

User File
A user file is a file created and managed by a user for personal or application-specific purposes.

File Control Block
File Control Block (FCB) is a data structure used by the operating system and file system to store metadata and management information about a file. It plays a central role in enabling name-based file access and is integral to the file directory structure, with each file typically associated with a single FCB that represents its directory entry. The FCB contains critical metadata such as file attributes, including size, creation date, and file type, as well as information related to file ownership and access permissions. It also maintains details about the file's physical location on storage, including direct block addresses, particularly useful for small files where efficient access is crucial. Additional data stored within the FCB may include access control information, such as password protection or user-specific access rights, depending on the operating system's security model. Together, these components allow the file system to manage file operations, enforce security policies, and ensure reliable access and retrieval of file data.

System File
A system file is a file used by the operating system for essential functions and operations.

Data Item
A data item is the lowest-level data organization unit in a file system, consisting of either a basic data item (a single attribute value) or a composite data item (a combination of multiple basic data items).

File Attribute
A file attribute, also known as file metadata, includes information such as file name, type, owner, size, creation time, access permissions, and location, maintained by the operating system.

File
A file is a collection of information stored on a disk, representing data such as text documents, images, or programs, and is managed by the operating system.<SEP>A file is a collection of data stored on the disk, managed by the file system and accessible through directory entries.<SEP>A file is an abstract data type representing a collection of data stored on a storage device, with operations defined by the operating system.<SEP>A file is a unit of data stored in a file system, associated with a directory entry that contains its metadata.<SEP>A file is a collection of data stored on a storage device, managed by the file system and associated with metadata such as name, location, and attributes.

Record
A record is a collection of related data items that describe properties of an object in a specific context, typically used in structured files.

Library File
A library file contains reusable code or data that can be linked with other programs during execution.

Target File
A target file is an intermediate output generated during the compilation process, containing machine code.

Directory File
A directory file is a special file used to organize and manage other files and subdirectories.

Read-Only File
A read-only file is a file that can be accessed for reading but not modified by users with limited permissions.

Regular File
A regular file is a standard file that contains data arranged in a conventional format, as opposed to special or directory files.

Executable File
An executable file is a compiled program that can be directly run by the operating system.

Source File
A source file contains human-readable code written by a programmer, typically used as input for compilation.

Read-Write File
A read-write file is a file that allows both reading and writing operations by authorized users.

Special File
A special file represents a device or system resource, such as a printer or terminal, and is managed by the operating system.

Secondary Storage
Secondary storage refers to non-volatile storage devices such as hard disks, where files are permanently stored.

Process
A process is a running instance of a program, serving as the basic unit of resource allocation and scheduling in the operating system.

File Size
File size is the amount of storage space a file occupies, typically measured in bytes, words, or blocks.

Disk
A disk is a storage device used to hold data persistently, such as a hard disk drive.<SEP>A disk is a physical storage medium that can be partitioned into volumes and used to store data.

User
A user is an individual who interacts with the computer system to create, access, modify, and manage files.<SEP>A user is an individual who interacts with the file system to perform operations such as creating, deleting, and managing files and directories.<SEP>A user is an individual or application that interacts with the file system to access or manage files, and requires name-based access to files.

File Access Permission
File access permission defines the level of access a user or process has to a file, including read, write, and execute rights.

Operating System
The Operating System is a system software that manages hardware and software resources, including file system operations.<SEP>The operating system manages file operations through system calls and maintains data structures like open file tables to track file states.

Creation Time
Creation time is the timestamp indicating when a file was first created in the system.

Last Modified Time
Last modified time is the timestamp indicating when the content of a file was last updated.

Structured File
A structured file is a file organized as a collection of records, typically used in database-style applications.

File Location
File location refers to the physical or logical address on a storage device where a file is stored, including device and path information.

File Metadata
File metadata consists of additional information about a file such as its owner, permissions, timestamps, and type, stored alongside the file data.

Character Stream
A character stream is a data structure representing a file as a sequence of characters, typical of unstructured files.

Last Accessed Time
Last accessed time is the timestamp indicating the most recent time a file was read or opened.

Relative Path
A relative path identifies a file based on the current working directory, allowing efficient file access within a localized scope.

User File Directory
The User File Directory (UFD) is a subordinate directory in the two-level structure, containing directory entries (FCBs) for all files belonging to a specific user.

Master File Directory
The Master File Directory (MFD) is the top level of the two-level directory structure, storing usernames and the locations of corresponding user file directories.

Tree-Structured Directory
The tree-structured directory extends the two-level directory by organizing directories in a hierarchical tree format, supporting efficient file classification and access via absolute and relative path names.

Absolute Path
An absolute path is a complete file reference starting from the root directory, uniquely identifying a file in the file system.

Current Directory
The current directory, also known as the working directory, is the directory from which a process operates, and all relative path references are resolved from this point.

Single-Level Directory Structure
The single-level directory structure maintains a single directory table for the entire file system, with each file occupying one directory entry, enabling name-based access but suffering from slow search, non-reusable file names, and poor file sharing.

Acyclic Graph Directory Structure
The acyclic graph directory structure extends the tree structure by allowing shared nodes, enabling multiple directory entries to point to the same file or subdirectory without forming cycles.

Shared Counter
A shared counter tracks the number of references to a shared file or directory node, ensuring safe deletion only when no users are referencing it.

Directory Table
The directory table is a centralized data structure in the single-level directory system that stores all directory entries for files in the file system.

Linux
Linux is an open-source operating system that uses a tree-structured directory system.

Windows
Windows is an operating system that employs a tree-structured directory system.

Unix
Unix is an operating system that implements a tree-structured directory system.

System Call
A system call is a function provided by the operating system to allow user processes to request services, such as changing the current directory.

Hard Link
Hard link is a file sharing method that creates a directory entry pointing to an index node, enabling multiple directories to reference the same file.

Disk Block
Disk block is a unit of storage on a disk drive, used to store parts of a file; new disk blocks may be allocated during file updates.<SEP>A Disk Block is a unit of storage space on a disk, used for storing data and indexed in the bit map.<SEP>A disk block is a fixed-size unit of storage on a disk, corresponding to a data block in a file.

Index Node
Index node stores file metadata and physical address information, and includes a count of directory entries linking to it.<SEP>The index node (inode) stores metadata and address information for a file, including up to 13 address entries in the UNIX system.<SEP>Index Node (inode) is a data structure in some systems like UNIX that separates file name from file metadata, storing file attributes and physical location information separately from directory entries.

File Sharing
File sharing allows multiple users to access a single copy of a file, reducing storage waste by avoiding duplicate file copies.<SEP>File sharing is a capability that allows multiple users to access and use the same file, supported by directory-based access control mechanisms.

Link Count
Link count, or reference count, tracks the number of directory entries that link to a specific index node.

Symbolic Link
Symbolic link, or soft link, is a file that contains the path to another file, enabling sharing without direct reference to the index node.

Nondirected Acyclic Graph Directory
Nondirected acyclic graph directory is a file system structure that supports efficient file sharing through linked directory entries.

Physical Address
Physical address refers to the disk block number of a file, which is stored in directory entries when linking files for sharing.

File Path Name
File path name is the string that specifies the location of a file in the directory hierarchy, used in symbolic links.

Network Address
Network address specifies the location of a file on a remote machine, used in network file sharing via symbolic links.

User A
User A is the original owner of a file and has direct access to its index node.

Index Node Count
Index node count indicates the number of directory entries linking to a specific index node; when zero, the file is deleted.

Link Type File
Link type file is a file of type LINK that contains a path name to another file; used in creating symbolic links.

File Access
File access refers to the process of reading or writing to a file, which may require multiple disk reads in symbolic linking scenarios.

User B
User B is a secondary user who shares a file with User A through a symbolic link or hard link.

Reference Count
Reference count, also known as link count, is a numeric value in an index node that tracks how many directory entries point to the file.

Master Boot Record
The Master Boot Record is located at the 0th sector of the disk and is responsible for booting the computer, containing a partition table and identifying the active partition.

Inode
An inode is a data structure that stores metadata about a file, with one inode per file, describing various file attributes.

Super Block
The super block stores critical file system information and is loaded into memory during system boot or initial file system use, including block count, block size, free block count, and pointers.

Free Blocks Information
Information about free blocks in the file system can be represented using a bitmap or linked list of pointers.

Root Directory
The root directory is the top-level directory in the file system's directory tree and is directly located after the i-nodes.

Active Partition
The active partition is the disk partition designated to be booted during system startup.

Partition Table
The partition table follows the Master Boot Record and contains the starting and ending addresses of each disk partition.

Boot Block
The boot block, located at the beginning of each partition, contains the program that starts the operating system for that partition; also known as the partition boot sector in Windows.

Mount Table
The mount table is stored in memory and holds information about each mounted file system partition.

Process Open File Table
Each process has its own open file table containing file descriptors (file handles in Windows) and pointers to entries in the system-wide open file table.<SEP>The Process Open File Table is a per-process data structure that stores process-specific file usage information, including read/write pointers and access modes.

Disk Partition
A disk partition is a logical division of a hard disk that acts as a separate unit for file system storage.

Directory Cache
The directory cache in memory stores recently accessed directory information to improve performance.

File System Layout
File system layout refers to the arrangement of data structures and storage areas on disk, including MBR, boot block, super block, inodes, directories, and files.

Block
A block is a fixed-size unit of storage used by the file system to manage data on disk.

Open File Table
The system-wide open file table contains copies of FCBs, open counts, and other data related to currently open files.<SEP>The Open File Table is a data structure maintained by the operating system that stores information about currently opened files, including file descriptors, access permissions, and pointers.

FCB
FCB (File Control Block) is a data structure that contains information about an open file, including file status, location, and access permissions.<SEP>FCB (File Control Block) is a data structure used to store metadata about a file, such as its location, size, permissions, and timestamp, and is stored in the directory area of a volume.

Memory Structure
The directory cache improves efficiency by storing frequently accessed directory entries in memory.

Close File
Close File is a system call that removes a file's entry from the process-specific open file table and decrements the system-wide open count.

Create File
Create File is a system-level operation that allocates storage space and adds a directory entry for a new file.<SEP>Create File is an operation that adds a new directory entry when a new file is created.

Read File
Read File is a system-level operation that locates the file in the directory, retrieves its storage address, and uses a read pointer to access data.

Open File
Open File is a system call that retrieves a file's directory entry from storage and loads it into memory, returning a file descriptor to the user.

Delete File
Delete File is a system-level operation that removes a file's directory entry, releases its control block, and recovers storage space.<SEP>Delete File is an operation that removes a directory entry when a file is deleted.

Write File
Write File is a system-level operation that locates the file using its directory entry and uses a write pointer to modify file data, updating the pointer with each operation.

System Open File Table
The System Open File Table is a global data structure containing file metadata such as disk location, size, and access date, shared across all processes.

File Pointer
The File Pointer is a per-process indicator that tracks the current read/write location within an open file.

Open Count
The Open Count is a counter in the system open file table that tracks the number of processes currently accessing a file.

File Descriptor
A file descriptor is an index returned by the operating system after opening a file, used to reference the file in subsequent I/O operations.

File Handle
A file handle is a system-internal identifier used in Windows to reference an open file, functionally equivalent to a file descriptor.

Access Permission
Access Permission is a field in the process open file table that defines the mode (e.g., read, write, append) under which a file is accessed.

Memory Buffer
The Memory Buffer is a temporary storage area in memory used to hold file data during read/write operations.<SEP>A memory buffer is allocated before disk block transfers to improve performance and manage data temporarily.

Disk Space
Disk Space refers to the physical storage capacity on a disk where file data and metadata are stored.

Write Pointer
Each write operation updates the write pointer to reflect the next write location.

Bit Map
The Bit Map is a data structure used to represent the allocation status of disk blocks, where each bit corresponds to a disk block.

data.entity_name: Memory Stack of Free Block Numbers
data.content:
Memory Stack of Free Block Numbers
The Memory Stack of Free Block Numbers is a data structure in memory that holds the starting block numbers of groups in the Group Linking Method.

Free Block Table
The Free Block Table is a data structure used to track free disk blocks, though it becomes impractical in large file systems.

Disk Capacity
Disk Capacity refers to the total storage volume of a disk, which directly affects the size of the bit map.

Bit Map Method
The Bit Map Method is a technique for managing free disk blocks by using a bitmap where each bit indicates whether a block is free or allocated.<SEP>The bit map method uses a binary map where each bit represents the status of a disk block (0 = free, 1 = allocated).

Free Block List
The Free Block List is a linked list structure used to maintain a record of free disk blocks, but it becomes too large for large file systems.

Group Linking Method
The Group Linking Method is a disk space management technique used in UNIX systems that groups free blocks and links them together to avoid long lists.

Allocation of Disk Blocks
The allocation of disk blocks involves assigning free blocks to users by updating the free block stack.

Reclamation of Disk Blocks
The reclamation of disk blocks involves returning used blocks to free space, updating the stack and potentially creating a new group.

i
The variable i represents the row index in the bit map, calculated as (b-1) DIV n + 1, where b is the block number and n is the number of columns.

j
The variable j represents the column index in the bit map, calculated as (b-1) MOD n + 1, where b is the block number and n is the number of columns.

b
The variable b represents the block number being processed in the bit map calculation.

Group Size
Group Size refers to the number of disk blocks in each group, such as 100 blocks per group in the Group Linking Method.

Block Number
A Block Number is a unique identifier for a disk block used in managing free block allocation.

n
The variable n represents the number of columns in the bit map, used in calculating the row and column indices.

File Storage Space Management
File storage space management involves organizing and allocating storage space on a device for file data and metadata, including partitioning, initializing volumes, and managing free blocks.

Storage Device
A storage device is a physical or logical unit capable of holding data, such as a disk or RAID set, which can be partitioned into volumes.

File Area
The file area is the portion of a volume allocated to store file data.

Partition
A partition is a logical division of a storage device, allowing multiple file systems to coexist on a single physical disk.

Physical Block
A physical block is a fixed-size unit of storage on a disk used for data transfer and management.<SEP>A Physical Block is a unit of storage on a disk used to hold data, managed through file allocation methods.

Free Block
A free block is a unit of storage space on a disk that is not currently allocated to any file.

Directory Area
The directory area is the portion of a volume allocated to store file control blocks (FCBs) and directory entries.

Free Table Method
The free table method is a continuous allocation technique that uses a table to keep track of free disk areas by listing block ranges.

Free Block Chain
The free block chain method maintains a linked list of individual free disk blocks, each pointing to the next.

Disk Initialization
Disk initialization is the process of setting up a volume with file system structures such as directory area, file area, and metadata tables.

Free Area Chain
The free area chain method manages free disk areas, where each area contains multiple adjacent blocks and links to the next area.

Best Fit Algorithm
The best fit algorithm selects the smallest free block that can accommodate a request, minimizing internal fragmentation.

First Fit Algorithm
The first fit algorithm is a memory and disk allocation strategy that allocates the first suitable free block or area found.

RAID Set
A RAID set is a collection of multiple disks configured together to provide redundancy, performance, or both.

Free Space Management
Free space management refers to the process of organizing, allocating, and reclaiming unused storage space on a device.

Superblock
The superblock is a data structure in a file system volume that stores metadata about the volume, including its size, block size, and status.

Physical Storage Mapping
The physical storage mapping involves creating algorithms and data structures to translate logical file system structures into physical disk addresses.

Logical File System
The logical file system manages metadata such as directory structures, file control blocks, and file protection without storing actual file content.

Basic File System
The basic file system sends generic read/write commands to device drivers and manages memory buffers and caches for disk blocks.

Interrupt Handler
An interrupt handler manages hardware interrupts to coordinate I/O operations and system responsiveness.

User Interface
The user interface of a file system defines file attributes, allowed file operations, and directory structure organization for user interaction.

Device Driver
A device driver translates high-level commands into hardware-specific instructions for I/O devices.

I/O Control Layer
The I/O control layer includes device drivers and interrupt handlers responsible for transferring information between memory and disk systems.

Logical Block Address
A logical block address is a sequential identifier assigned to data blocks within a file, starting from 0 and not directly corresponding to physical locations.

File Organization Module
The file organization module maps logical block addresses to physical block addresses and manages free space allocation.

File Protection
File protection mechanisms control access rights to files based on user identity or roles.<SEP>File protection is a mechanism designed to prevent unauthorized access, modification, or destruction of files by controlling user permissions.

Physical Block Address
A physical block address identifies a specific location on a physical storage device where data is stored.

Free Space Manager
The free space manager tracks unallocated disk blocks and allocates them as needed to files.

Disk Address
A disk address uniquely identifies a physical block on a storage device.

Read Access
Read access allows a user to retrieve data from a file without modifying it.

Write Access
Write access enables a user to modify or add data to a file.

Password Protection
Password protection is a method where a user sets a password for a file, which must be provided to gain access, ensuring controlled sharing.

Encryption Protection
Encryption protection secures files by encrypting their contents, requiring a key for decryption during access, ensuring confidentiality.

Execute Access
Execute access permits a user to load a file into memory and run it as a program.

Access Control List
An Access Control List (ACL) is a data structure associated with a file or directory that specifies which users or system processes are granted access to objects, and what operations are allowed.

Add Access
Add access allows a user to append new data to the end of a file.

Other Users
Other users refers to all system users who are not the owner or part of the specified group.

Owner
The owner is the user who creates a file and typically has full control over its permissions and access.

List Access
List access allows a user to view file names and their attributes within a directory.

Group
A group is a collection of users who share similar access needs to a file or directory.

Encryption Key
An encryption key is a piece of data used to encrypt or decrypt a file during access.

Delete Access
Delete access grants the ability to remove a file and reclaim associated storage space.

Dentry Object
The Dentry Object represents a directory entry in a path, containing pointers to the associated inode, parent directory, and child directories; it is created dynamically during path traversal and has no corresponding structure on disk.

File Object
The File Object represents an open file from a process perspective, containing file system context, file pointer, and operations; it links to the inode and is associated with a specific process.

Virtual File System
The Virtual File System (VFS) abstracts differences between file systems and provides a unified interface for file operations, allowing users to interact with files without considering underlying file systems or storage media.

Close Function
The close function is a system call used to close an open file, releasing associated resources and removing the file object.

Superblock Object
The Superblock Object represents a mounted file system and stores metadata about the file system, with operations such as allocating and destroying inodes, reading and writing inodes.

Open Function
The open function is a system call used to open a file, which triggers the creation of a file object and initiates file access.

Inode Object
The Inode Object represents a specific file and maintains metadata, with operations including creating new inodes, hard links, and directories; it is created in memory when a file is accessed.

File System Interface
The File System Interface is a standardized set of operations defined by VFS that all file systems must support to be compatible with the system.

File System Metadata
File System Metadata contains information about a file system, such as size, block count, and status, stored primarily in the superblock.

Mounting Process
The Mounting Process refers to the operation of attaching a file system to the virtual file system hierarchy, enabling access to its files and data.

Memory Management
Memory Management refers to the dynamic allocation and deallocation of memory for VFS objects such as Superblock, Inode, Dentry, and File Objects during system operation.

Path Resolution
Path Resolution is the process by which the VFS traverses a file path, transforming it into a sequence of Dentry Objects for file access.

Continuous Allocation
Continuous Allocation requires a file to occupy contiguous disk blocks, enabling efficient sequential and direct access but causing external fragmentation.

File Allocation Method
File Allocation Method determines how disk blocks are assigned to files and includes continuous, linked, and indexed allocation.

Disk Block Management
Disk Block Management involves the organization and tracking of disk space, including non-empty and empty blocks.

Logical File
A Logical File is an abstract representation of a file, where records are stored in a defined sequence.

Linked Allocation
Linked Allocation assigns non-contiguous disk blocks and links them via pointers, eliminating external fragmentation but limiting direct access.

Indexed Allocation
Indexed Allocation uses an index block to store all block addresses of a file, enabling direct access while avoiding external fragmentation.

Disk I/O
Disk I/O refers to data transfer between memory and disk, performed in units of blocks.

Main Index
The Main Index is a higher-level index that points to second-level indices, used in multi-level indexing schemes.

External Fragmentation
External Fragmentation occurs when free disk space is scattered, preventing efficient allocation of large contiguous blocks.

File Directory Entry
A File Directory Entry stores metadata such as the starting block number and file size.<SEP>A file directory entry is a single unit within a file directory that represents a file and contains metadata such as attributes, location, and ownership, equivalent to a File Control Block (FCB).

File Allocation Table
File Allocation Table (FAT) is a system-wide table that stores pointers to disk blocks, enabling efficient access and space management.

Second-Level Index
A Second-Level Index is used in multi-level indexing to manage large files by linking multiple index blocks.

Index Block
An Index Block contains a list of disk block numbers for a file, used in indexed allocation.<SEP>An index block is a disk block used to store addresses of data blocks or other index blocks in a multi-level indexing scheme.

FAT Table Entry
A FAT Table Entry stores the address of the next disk block or special values like -1 (end of file) or -2 (free block).

Implicit Linking
Implicit Linking is a form of linked allocation where block pointers are stored within the blocks themselves, making them transparent to the user.

Explicit Linking
Explicit Linking is a form of linked allocation where block pointers are stored in a centralized File Allocation Table (FAT), allowing faster access and better management.

FAT
FAT (File Allocation Table) is a system-wide data structure that tracks the allocation status of disk blocks and contains pointers to the next block in a file chain.

Master Index
The master index is a higher-level index that holds block numbers of the first, second, and subsequent secondary index blocks.

Secondary Index Allocation
Secondary index allocation is a method that uses a master index table to store block addresses of secondary index blocks, enabling efficient lookup for large files, and operates similarly to multi-level page tables in memory management.

Multi-Level Index
Multi-level index allocation extends the secondary index method to three or more levels to manage extremely large files by nesting index structures.

Two-Level Index Allocation
Two-level index allocation uses a master index pointing to secondary index blocks, which in turn contain data block addresses, ideal for large files.

Single-Level Index Allocation
Single-level index allocation uses one index block to store the block numbers of file data, suitable for medium-sized files.

Direct Addressing
Direct addressing stores the block numbers of file data directly in the file control block, typically used for small files to speed up access.<SEP>Direct Addressing is a technique used by index nodes to store direct block references in the first few address fields.

Three-Level Index Allocation
Three-level index allocation extends the two-level approach by adding an additional indexing layer for very large files.

Hybrid Index Allocation
Hybrid index allocation combines direct, single-level, two-level, and three-level indexing to optimize performance across various file sizes.

Address Item
Address items in an index node refer to the specific fields used to store block addresses, such as i.addr(0) to i.addr(12).

i.addr(10)
This address item in the UNIX index node is used for single-level indirect addressing, pointing to a single index block.

i.addr(11)
This address item in the UNIX index node is used for double indirect addressing, pointing to a level-two index block.

i.addr(12)
This address item in the UNIX index node is used for triple indirect addressing, enabling access to very large files through a three-level indexing system.

i.addr(0) to i.addr(9)
These are the first ten direct address items in the UNIX index node, used to store direct block numbers for small files.

Large File
A large file is a file that exceeds typical storage limits and requires multi-level or hybrid indexing for efficient management.

Very Large File
A very large file is a data object that necessitates three or more levels of indexing to be efficiently accessed and stored.

Access Speed
Access speed refers to the rate at which data can be read from or written to storage, influenced by the indexing method.

Data Block
A data block is a sector on a disk that contains actual file data.

Medium File
A medium file is a file of intermediate size that benefits from single-level index allocation.

UNIX System
The UNIX system is an operating system that implements a hybrid index allocation strategy using 13 address entries in its index node.

Small File
A small file is a file with minimal size, suitable for direct addressing to optimize access speed.

Disk Seek
Disk seek is the time required for the disk head to move to the correct track, increasing with the number of index levels.

No External Fragmentation
Linked Allocation avoids external fragmentation because blocks do not need to be contiguous.

Direct Access Support
Indexed Allocation enables direct access to any file block via an index block.

Multi-Level Indexing
Multi-Level Indexing uses a Second-Level Index to manage very large files that exceed a single index block.

Efficient Access
Continuous Allocation supports both sequential and direct file access, making it efficient for reading.

Sequential Access Only
Linked Allocation supports only sequential access, making direct access inefficient.

Index Level
Disk seek time increases with the number of index levels due to additional disk accesses.

File Owner Identifier
File Owner Identifier is a value that uniquely identifies the user or group that owns a file.

Memory Index Node
Memory Index Node is a copy of the disk index node loaded into memory when a file is opened, enhanced with additional runtime status and access tracking information.

Disk Index Node
Disk Index Node is the version of an index node stored on disk, containing file metadata such as owner, type, permissions, physical addresses, and timestamps.

File Physical Address
File Physical Address refers to the disk block locations where the actual data of a file is stored, accessible via the index node.

File Type
File Type specifies whether a file is a regular file, directory, or special file.

File Link Count
File Link Count is the number of directory entries (hard links) pointing to a specific file.

File Length
File Length is the size of the file in bytes, stored as part of the index node.

Index Node Number
Index Node Number is a unique identifier used to reference a specific index node in memory or on disk.

File Access Permissions
File Access Permissions define the access rights granted to the file owner, authorized users, and general users.

Access Count
Access Count tracks how many processes are currently accessing a memory index node.

File Modification Time
File Modification Time indicates the last time the files content was modified.

File Access Time
File Access Time records the last time a file was accessed or modified, used for file management.

Status Flag
Status Flag indicates whether an index node is locked or has been modified.

Logical Device Number
Logical Device Number identifies the file system to which a file belongs.

Indirect Addressing
Indirect Addressing allows index nodes to store addresses of other blocks that contain additional physical block addresses.

Link Pointer
Link Pointer is used to connect memory index nodes to free lists or hash queues for efficient management.

Status
Status in Memory Index Node indicates whether the node is locked or modified, aiding process coordination.

File Creation Time
File Control Block records the time when the file was created.

Delete Directory
Delete Directory is an operation that removes a directory; it may require deleting all contained files and subdirectories depending on the implementation.

Display Directory
Display Directory is an operation that shows the contents and attributes of a directory to the user.

Move Directory
Move Directory is an operation that relocates a file or subdirectory between parent directories, altering the path name.

Directory Operations
Directory operations are fundamental actions performed on directory structures in a file system, including search, create, delete, move, display, and modify.

Create Directory
Create Directory is an operation that allows users to establish a new directory or subdirectory in a hierarchical structure.

Search
Search is an operation that locates a file's directory entry within the directory structure.

Modify Directory
Modify Directory is an operation that alters directory entries when file attributes stored within the directory change.

Tree Structured Directory
Tree structured directory is a hierarchical directory system where directories can contain subdirectories and files.

Subdirectory
A subdirectory is a directory contained within another directory in a tree-structured file system.

User Directory
A user directory is a personal directory created by a user in a file system to store their own files and subdirectories.

Path Name
A path name is the hierarchical reference to a file or directory, which changes when the file or directory is moved.

Name-Based Access
Name-based access is a method that allows users to locate files using human-readable names instead of physical addresses, facilitated by directory mapping.

File Retrieval Speed
File retrieval speed refers to the efficiency with which a system can locate and access a file through the directory, impacting overall system performance.

Tree Structure
A tree structure is a hierarchical data structure used in directory management to organize files and subdirectories, enabling efficient navigation and resolution of file names.

Multiple Users
Multiple users refer to a multi-user computing environment where several individuals can interact with the system and share files, requiring directory support for name and access management.

Access Control
Access control is a technique used in directory management to regulate permissions and restrict or permit user access to files based on predefined policies.
